title: USDA - National Agricultural Statistics Service - Census of Agriculture
description: The Census of Agriculture is a complete count of U.S. farms and ranches and the people who operate them. Even small plots of land - whether rural or urban - growing fruit, vegetables or some food animals count if $1,000 or more of such products were raised and sold, or normally would have been sold, during the Census year. The Census of Agriculture, taken only once every five years, looks at land use and ownership, operator characteristics, production practices, income and expenditures. For America's farmers and ranchers, the Census of Agriculture is their voice, their future, and their opportunity.

title: USDA LincPass Program | USDA
description: What is a LincPass? The LincPass is your departmentally issued identification credential which will allow you to access both USDA facilities and information systems. The LincPass was named after President Lincoln and is the commonly used name for the Personal Identity Verification (PIV) card at USDA. The LincPass is the only credential issued at USDA that meets the standards of Homeland Security Presidential Directive 12 (HSPD-12).

title: USDA - National Agricultural Statistics Service Homepage
description: USDA National Agricultural Statistics Service Information. NASS publications cover a wide range of subjects, from traditional crops, such as corn and wheat, to specialties, such as mushrooms and flowers; from calves born to hogs slaughtered; from agricultural prices to land in farms. The agency has the distinction of being known as The Fact Finders of U.S. Agriculture due to the abundance of information we produce. The National Agricultural Statistics Service's mission is to serve the United States, its agriculture, and its rural communities by providing meaningful, accurate, and objective statistical information and services.
